\begin_layout Standard
As Saulson and González neatly described 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "saulson1990thermal,Gonz\\'alez199512,1995PhDT........16G"

\end_inset

, all mechanical oscillators have intrinsic thermal noise.
 Through the fluctuation-dissipation theorem, any lossy oscillator at finite
 temperature drives itself with thermal fluctuations.
 The intrinsic noise in a torsion balance is known to be consistent with
 thermal noise from 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

internal damping
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, that is, that the spring constant has an imaginary part.
 
\begin_inset Formula $I\ddot{\theta}=\kappa\theta\rightarrow I\ddot{\theta}=\kappa(1+i\frac{1}{Q})\theta$
\end_inset

 , where 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa$
\end_inset

 is the torsion constant of the fiber, 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 the pendulum's moment of inertia about the fiber axis, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 the pendulum twist angle.
 This is in contrast to more-familiar external damping, where 
\begin_inset Formula $I\ddot{\theta}=-\kappa\theta-\frac{\sqrt{\kappa I}}{Q}\dot{\theta}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A torsion balance suspended in sufficiently high vacuum is 'internally damped'.
 Following Saulson's classic explication, internal damping gives rise to
 torque noise power with a 
\begin_inset Formula $1/f$
\end_inset

 spectral shape.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In torque units, the expected thermal noise power is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\tau^{2}(f)=4k_{B}T\frac{\kappa}{2\pi fQ}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Gas damping
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Origin
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As we considered in a detailed investigation of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

squeeze-film damping
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

proximity-enhanced gas damping
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "schlamminger2010indirect,cavalleri2009increased,dolesi2011brownian"

\end_inset

, torsion balances in imperfect vacuum are damped by the residual atmosphere.
 Microscopically, there is only one form of gas damping - collisions between
 gas particles and an oscillator allow momentum and energy exchange.
 Experimentally, when the particle mean free path is larger than the dimensions
 of the chamber, gas damping appears in two forms: 'free' damping and 'proximity
-enhanced' damping.
 Free gas damping is independent of an oscillator's location in a vacuum
 chamber, and depends only upon properties of the gas and the dimensions
 of the pendulum.
 For a rectangular pendulum with moment of inertia 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

, resonant frequency 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{o}$
\end_inset

, width 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

, and height 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 immersed in a gas with pressure 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

, temperature 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

, and molecular mass 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Q_{unconstrained}=\frac{32\pi If_{0}\sqrt{8k_{B}T/(\pi m)}}{l^{3}hP}\alpha.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There remains some disagreement in the literature regarding the coefficient
 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

, which takes values of 
\begin_inset Formula $16/\pi$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $16$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $24$
\end_inset

.
 For both theoretical and experimental reasons, we prefer 16 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "schlamminger2010indirect"

\end_inset

.
 For PlateWash the final operating pressure was 
\begin_inset CommandInset include
LatexCommand input
filename "../systematics/pressure/extracted/finalPressurePa.tex"

\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Pa, implying a 
\begin_inset Formula $Q\sim$
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset include
LatexCommand input
filename "../systematics/pressure/extracted/unconstrainedQ.tex"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Proximity-enhanced gas damping is geometry dependent.
 It arises in regions of constrained gas flow.
 Restricted volumes of gas that are compressed/rarified by oscillator motion
 have slight over/under-pressure that opposes the oscillator's motion.
 If the restricted volume's equilibration time 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{eq}$
\end_inset

 is comparable to the oscillator period 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

, the effect becomes lossy.
 If the constrained flow is determined by a distance of closest-proximity,
 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{1}{Q_{PED}}=\frac{1}{Q}\left(\alpha+\frac{\sqrt{8k_{B}T/(\pi m)}\tau_{eq}(d)}{d}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{eq}(d)$
\end_inset

 is, in general, a complicated function of oscillator/chamber geometry.
 The scaling of 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{eq}(d)$
\end_inset

 is approximately a fractional power law for most geometries, with connections
 to an underlying Lévy walk of the gas molecules.
 Analytical approximations exist for certain geometries, but in any application
 where these effects matter quantitatively, experimentation and accurate
 Monte Carlo simulation is essential.
 Our experiments with PlateWash showed that, for small 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $Q\propto d^{1.6\pm0.3}$
\end_inset

; our simulations predicted 
\begin_inset Formula $Q\propto d^{1.85}$
\end_inset

.
 At the pressures and separations used in this inverse square law test,
 the implied gas damping Q is approximately 800.
\end_layout

